queryEngine.description: Sample queries demonstrating how the knowledge graph enables intelligent harvest predictions with validation

queries.question: When should I plant Cherokee Purple tomatoes in South Florida (Zone 10)?
When will I harvest if I plant Cherokee Purple in Zone 10 on August 15?

validation.agreement: All sources agree on October-December window from fall planting

queries.question: What's the best tomato cultivar for Zone 10b heat tolerance?

features: Sets fruit in wide temperature range

topRecommendations.note: Best quality but less forgiving of heat - plant in optimal windows

result.recommendation: For maximum reliability in Zone 10b heat, use Floradade or Homestead. For premium flavor with careful timing, use Cherokee Purple in fall/winter windows.

queries.question: Validate: Does Cypress Creek Farm's Nov-Apr harvest window match predictions?

validation.assessment: Farm timing (Nov-Apr) perfectly matches the CORE harvest window predicted by all sources. Falls within state calendar, aligns with seed company fall planting predictions, and matches extension guidance.
validation.triangulation: 4-way agreement: State + Extension + Seed companies + Farm data

queries.question: Compare data quality: State calendar vs Extension vs Seed companies vs Farms

result.optimalStrategy: Use all four in concert: Extension + Seed companies for initial predictions, State calendar for validation, Farm data for ground truth confirmation. Highest confidence when all four sources agree.

queries.question: Predict Brix for Cherokee Purple in Zone 10 harvested mid-December

result.reasoning: Harvested in peak window (Nov-Dec) when all sources agree quality is optimal. Heritage cultivar at genetic ceiling with proper timing.

validation.description: How the knowledge graph validates predictions through multi-source triangulation

discrepancyHandling.description: What to do when sources disagree

rules.scenario: Days to maturity varies across seed companies
rules.example: Cherokee Purple: Johnny's 72, Burpee 80, Mary's 85 → consensus 80

rules.scenario: Farm reports earlier/later timing than predictions
rules.resolution: Flag as microclimate variation or practice-dependent

rules.scenario: Extension research conflicts with state calendar
rules.rationale: Extension data is variety-specific, state calendar is aggregate

rules.scenario: Seed company timing seems too conservative
rules.resolution: Use as minimum safe window, extension as optimal
rules.rationale: Commercial seed companies provide conservative guidance to prevent customer failure

investorNarrative.theProposition: Fielder has built the world's first agricultural intelligence knowledge graph that predicts AND validates harvest timing and quality through multi-source triangulation.
theDataMoat: Layer 3: Seed company data (public, but product-first organization)
Layer 4: Farm ground truth (private, Fielder exclusive)
investorNarrative.whyItMatters: No one else has connected these four public data sources into an integrated intelligence system. The farm data + measurement validation creates the defensible moat.
investorNarrative.theNetworkEffect: Every scan → more data → better predictions → higher trust → more scans. The flywheel accelerates with scale.

competitiveMoat.cantBeScraped: Farm timing data is relationship-based (LocalHarvest partnerships)
competitiveMoat.cantBeSynthesized: Measurement pairs (prediction → actual) require real-world validation
competitiveMoat.cantBeBought: Data accumulates over seasons - time is the moat

investorNarrative.goToMarketProof: Fresh Gardens (Zone 10b) reports lychee June-July. State calendar says May-July peak June-July. UF/IFAS says June-July harvest. All three agree → Fielder can predict with 95% confidence when Fresh Gardens' lychee will be available BEFORE asking them.

integrationExamples.title: Zone 10 Year-Round Food System
integrationExamples.description: Combining perennial tree crops with seasonal vegetables for continuous production

components.benefit: Year-round fruit production, permanent carbon sequestration

components.description: Perennial trees provide shade, nitrogen fixing, and soil building while annual vegetables rotate in understory for peak seasonal nutrition. This creates a regenerative system where perennials improve soil over time, reducing inputs needed for annuals.
